{"parse":{"title":"window","pageid":20622,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"==English==\n{{swp|<dab!>}}\n[[File:Gordijnen aan venster.JPG|thumb|A '''window''', viewed from inside.]]\n\n===Etymology===\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*h₂weh₁-|*h₃ekʷ-}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|wyndowe}}, {{m|enm|wyndown}}, from {{der|en|non|vindauga|t=window|lit=wind-eye; wind-hole}}, equivalent to {{com|en|wind|eye|nocat=1}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|windae}} and {{m|sco|windock}}, {{cog|fo|vindeyga}}, {{cog|nb|vindu}}, {{cog|nn|vindauge}}, {{cog|da|vindue}}, archaic {{cog|sv|vindöga}}, {{cog|ovd|windog}}. Displaced native {{ncog|ang|ēagþȳrel|lit=eye hole}} (the rare direct descendant is {{m|en|eyethurl||window, pupil, etc.}}). The “windows” among early Germanic peoples were just unglazed holes (eyes) in the wall or roof that permitted wind to pass through {{rfv-etym|en}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{a|en|UK}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈwɪndəʊ/|a=RP}}\n*** {{audio|en|En-uk-window.ogg|a=Southern England}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈwɪndo/|a=Scotland}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈwɪndou/|a=Wales,non-toe-tow}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈwɪndə/|a=Northumbria}}\n* {{enPR|wĭnʹdō|a=US}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈwɪndoʊ/}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-window.ogg|a=US}}\n** {{enPR|wĭnʹdə|a=colloquial,folk speech,nonstandard}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈwɪndə/}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈwɪndəʉ/|a=AU}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈwəndɐʉ/|a=NZ}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɪndəʊ|s=2}}\n* {{hyphenation|en|win|dow}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{wp|,+ (computing)}}\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# An opening, usually covered by one or more panes of clear glass, to allow light and air from outside to enter a building or vehicle.\n#: {{ux|en| She opened the '''window''' to let some air in.}}\n#* {{RQ:Jefferies Amateur Poacher|chapter=1|passage=But then I had the [massive] flintlock by me for protection. ¶{{...}}The linen-press and a chest on the top of it formed, however, a very good gun-carriage; and, thus mounted, aim could be taken out of the '''window''' at the old mare feeding in the meadow below by the brook, and a 'bead' could be drawn upon Molly, the dairymaid, kissing the fogger behind the hedge,{{nb...}}.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1952|author=w:L. F. Salzman|title=Building in England|page=173\n|passage=A '''window''' is an opening in a wall to admit light and air.}}\n#* {{RQ:Allingham China Governess|chapter=14|passage=Nanny Broome was looking up at the outer wall.&nbsp; Just under the ceiling there were three lunette '''windows''', heavily barred and blacked out in the normal way by centuries of grime.}}\n# An opening, usually covered by glass, in a shop which allows people to view the shop and its products from outside; a [[shop window]].\n#* {{RQ:Birmingham Gossamer|chapter=I|passage=There is an hour or two, after the passengers have embarked, which is disquieting and fussy.{{...}}Passengers wander restlessly about or hurry, with futile energy, from place to place. Pushing men hustle each other at the '''windows''' of the purser's office, under pretence of expecting letters or despatching telegrams.}}\n# {{lb|en|architecture|nocat=1}} The [[shutter]], [[casement]], [[sash]] with its fittings, or other [[framework]], which closes a window opening.\n# {{lb|en|figurative}} A period of time when something is available or possible; a limited [[opportunity]].\n#: {{co|en|launch '''window'''}}\n#: {{co|en|'''window''' of opportunity}}\n#: {{ux|en|You have a two-hour '''window''' of clear weather to finish working on the lawn.}}\n#* {{quote-web|en|author=Euan McKirdy; Hilary Whiteman|title=Thai cave rescue: Divers enter cave to free boys|work=edition.cnn.com|url=https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/thai-cave-rescue-live-intl/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=2018-07-08|accessdate=2018-07-08|passage=But rescuers have a dwindling '''window''' of opportunity, with forecasters predicting the return of heavy monsoon rains in the coming days, effectively sealing off the cave until October.}}\n#* {{quote-web|en|author=Euan McKirdy; et al.|work=edition.cnn.com|title=Arrest warrant to be issued for former Thai PM Yingluck Shinawatra|publisher=CNN|date=2017-08-25|accessdate=2017-08-25|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/08/24/asia/yingluck-shinawatra-trial-verdict/index.html|passage=Now she'll be thinking about fleeing. (The verdict delay) provides a '''window''' for potential flight....if she has not fled already.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2019 November 6|title=Network News|journal=Rail|page=26|text=An extensive period of trial running will then take place in the first quarter of 2020. The full opening of the Elizabeth Line is still planned to be within a six-month '''window''' between October 2020 and March 2021.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en-GB|author=Luke Harding|quotee={{w|Institute for the Study of War}}|title=Russian forces make significant gains in eastern Ukraine|work=The Guardian|date=2024-04-23|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2024/apr/23/russian-forces-make-significant-gains-in-eastern-ukraine|issn=0261-3077|author2=Dan Sabbagh|passage=“The Russian military command is likely aware of the closing window before more western aid arrives and is trying to secure offensive gains before the '''window''' closes,” it said in a briefing on Monday.}}\n# {{lb|en|figurative}} Something that allows one to see through or into something.\n#: {{ux|en|His journal provides a rare '''window''' into his otherwise obscure life.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=17 Dec 77|volume=5|number=24|journal=Gay Community News|page=4|author=Circle of Loving Companions|title=Critical Friends|text=Then we read Spear's confrontational commentary on the \"Richard Pryor Incident\" from the Black perspective...and suddenly we began to feel that GCN's '''window''' on the Gay World was something we couldn't live ''without'' since no other Gay Media voice seemed so speaking.}}\n# A restricted range.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2015|author=Patrick R. Nicolas|title=Scala for Machine Learning|page=109\n|passage=In this case, a band-pass filter using a range or '''window''' of frequencies is appropriate to isolate the frequency or the group of frequencies that characterize a specific cycle.}}\n# {{senseid|en|Q835016}} {{lb|en|graphical user interface}} A rectangular area on a computer [[terminal]] or screen containing some kind of [[user interface]], displaying [[output]] and allowing [[input]], often for a single task in a [[multitasking]] system.\n# A [[figure]] formed of [[line]]s [[cross]]ing each other.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1709|author={{w|William King (poet)|William King}}|title=Art of Cookery\n|passage=till he has '''windows''' on his bread and butter}}\n# {{lb|en|medicine}} The time between first infection and detectability.\n# {{lb|en|military|historical|uncountable}} {{synonym of|en|chaff||strips of material intended to confuse radar}} <!--this was the British code name-->\n# {{lb|en|signal processing}} A function multiplied with a signal to reduce spectral leakage when performing a Fourier transform.\n# {{lb|en|geology}} A [[fenster]]: a geologic or [[tectonic window]]. \n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1927|author=Léon William Collet|title=The Structure of the Alps|page=232\n|text={{...}}the Hohe Tauern '''window'''. In the transverse depression between the '''windows''', the Silvretta Nappe disappears almost entirely underneath the Oetztal Nappe. The southern margin of the Northern Limestone zone is formed by the \"Greywacke zone\" of{{nb...}}}}\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{sense|glass-covered opening}} {{l|en|glass}}\n\n====Coordinate terms====\n* {{sense|glass-covered opening}} {{l|en|door}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col4|en|title=Terms derived from ''window'' (noun)\n|anabolic window\n|awning window|window money\n|bay window\n|boob window|truth window\n|bow window|store window|window sitter\n|[[broken windows theory]] ([[broken window theory]])\n|cabinet window\n|casement window|fly window|valence window|window-breaker\n|Catherine-wheel window|time window out|window down|window out|window over|window up\n|cochlear window|window card|witch window\n|coffin window\n|compass window\n|dialog window\n|dormer-window,dormer window,dormant window\n|drop window\n|electric window\n|[[French window|French]] [[french window|(french) window]]\n|gable window\n|garret window\n|go out of the window,go out the window<!--idiom-->\n|Jesse window\n|Johari window\n|Judas window,judas window\n|Kaiser window|broken window|when God closes a door he opens a window|window gardener\n|lancet window\n|lattice window\n|launch window\n|loop-window\n|low side window\n|lucarne window\n|luthern window,luthern-window\n|maintenance window\n|make a better door than a window\n|marigold window|window system\n|mezzanine window\n|mullion window\n|Norman window\n|not have a pot to piss in or a window to throw it out of\n|ogive window\n|one-window\n|opera window\n|opportunity window\n|oriel window\n|out of the window,out the window\n|oval window\n|Overton window\n|palette window\n|Palladian window\n|picture window\n|process window index\n|re-entry window\n|rose window\n|round window\n|sash window\n|shop window\n|show window\n|silly window syndrome\n|sliding window\n|storm window\n|the eyes are the window to the soul\n|therapeutic window\n|time window\n|transfer window\n|transom window\n|trap window\n|trellis window\n|unwindow,unwindowed\n|vestibular window\n|weather window\n|wheel window\n|window back\n|window bar\n|window blind\n|window box\n|window cleaner\n|window covering\n|window curtain\n|window detector\n|window display\n|window-down\n|window-dress,window dresser,window dressing,window-dressing\n|windowed\n|window envelope\n|window fly\n|window frame\n|windowfront\n|window gardening\n|window glass\n|windowing\n|window-kill\n|window ledge\n|windowless\n|window licker\n|window lock\n|windowlike\n|window manager\n|window of discourse\n|window of opportunity\n|window of time\n|window on the world\n|window pane,windowpane\n|window plant\n|Windows<!--operating system-->\n|window sash\n|window screen\n|window seat,window-seat\n|[[window-shopping]]<!--\"window-shop\" is a back-formation-->, [[window shopping]] → [[window-shop]], [[window-shopper]]\n|window sill,windowsill\n|window stool\n|window swallow\n|window tax\n|window treatment\n|window washer\n}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|en|eye}}\n* {{l|en|wind}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|opening for light and air}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Abkhaz: {{t+|ab|аԥенџьыр}}\n* Afar: {{t+|aa|taagat}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|venster}}\n* Akkadian: {{t+|akk|𒀊|tr=[[Image:B223ellst.png|40px]] aptu, AB|f}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|dritare|f}}\n* Altai:\n*: Southern Altai: {{t+|alt|кӧзнӧк}}\n* Amharic: {{t+|am|መስኮት}}\n* Antillean Creole: {{t+|gcf|finèt}}, {{t+|gcf|founèt}}, {{t+|gcf|funèt}}, {{t+|gcf|fénèt}}\n* Arabic: {{t+|ar|نَافِذَة|f}}, {{t+|ar|شُبَّاك|m}}, {{t+|ar|طَاقَة|f}}\n*: Algerian Arabic: {{t+|arq|تاقة}}\n*: Chadian Arabic: {{t+|shu|شباك|m|tr=šubbāk}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{t+|arz|شباك|m|tr=šebbāk, šobbāk}}\n*: Gulf Arabic: {{t+|afb|دريشة|f|tr=dirīša}}\n*: Hijazi Arabic: {{t+|acw|شباك|m|tr=šubbāk}}, {{t+|acw|طاقة|f|tr=ṭāga}} {{qualifier|dated}}\n*: Iraqi Arabic: {{t+|acw|شباج|m|tr=šubbāč}}\n*: Juba Arabic: {{t+|pga|shubaak}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{t+|ary|طاقة|f|tr=ṭāqa}}, {{t+|ary|تاقة|f|tr=tāqa}},  {{t+|ary|شبيك|m|tr=šubbīk}}, {{t+|ary|شرجم|m}}, {{t+|ary|سرجم|m}}, {{t+|ary|سرجب|m}}, {{t+|ary|شرجب|m}}\n*: North Levantine Arabic: {{t+|apc|شباك|m|tr=šibbēk}} {{q|Lebanon}}\n*: South Levantine Arabic: {{t+|ajp|شباك|m|tr=šubbāk}}\n*: Sudanese Arabic: {{t+|apd|شباك|m|tr=šubbāk}}\n* Aragonese: {{t+|an|finestra|f}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Assyrian Neo-Aramaic: {{t+|aii|ܟܵܘܬܵܐ|f|tr=kāwtā}}, {{t+|aii|ܦܲܢܓ̰ܵܪܵܐ|m|tr=panjārā}}\n*: Classical Syriac: {{t+|syc|ܟܘܬܐ|f|tr=kawwəṯā}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|պատուհան}}, {{t+|hy|լուսամուտ}}, {{t+|hy|փանջարա}}\n* Aromanian: {{t+|rup|firidã|f}}, {{t+|rup|fireastrã|f}}\n* Assamese: {{t+|as|খিৰিকী}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|ventana|f}}\n* Atayal: {{t+|tay|nyaway}}\n* Aukan: {{t+|djk|fensee}}\n* Avar: {{t+|av|гордо}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t+|az|pəncərə}}\n* Baba Malay: {{t+|mbf|menyelah}}\n* Bakhtiari: {{t+|bqi|بنجه|tr=banja}}\n* Baluchi: {{t+|bal|دریگ|tr=darīg}}, {{t+|bal|دریچگ|tr=darīčag}}, {{t+|bal|دریچه|tr=darīča}}\n* Banjarese: {{t+|bjn|lalungkang}}\n* Bashkir: {{t+|ba|тәҙрә}}\n* Basque: {{t+|eu|leiho}}\n* Belarusian: {{t+|be|акно́|n}}, {{t+|be|вакно́|n}}, {{t+|be|аке́нца|n}} {{qualifier|diminutive}}\n* Bengali: {{t+|bn|জানালা}}\n* Bhojpuri: {{t+|bho|खिड़की}}\n* Bikol:\n*: Central Bikol: {{t+|bcl|bintana}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|prenestr|m}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|прозо́рец|m}}\n* Burmese: {{t+|my|ပြတင်းပေါက်}}, {{t+|my|လေသာပေါက်}}\n* Buryat: {{t+|bua|сонхо}}\n* Carpathian Rusyn: {{t+|rue|окно́|n}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|finestra|f}}\n* Cebuano: {{t+|ceb|bintana}}\n* Chamicuro: {{t+|ccc|wentana}}\n* Chechen: {{t+|ce|кор}}\n* Cherokee: {{t+|chr|ᏦᎳᏅ}}, {{t+|chr|ᏦᎳᏂ}}\n* Chichewa: {{t+|ny|zenera}}\n* Chickasaw: {{t+|cic|aahashtahli'}}, {{t+|cic|winda'}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t+|yue|窗|tr=coeng1}}, {{t+|yue|窗門|tr=coeng1 mun4-2}}\n*: Dungan: {{t+|dng|чуонхў}}, {{t+|dng|чуонзы}}\n*: Eastern Min: {{t+|cdo|檻門囝|tr=kāng-muòng-giāng}}, {{t+|cdo|檻門|tr=kāng-muòng}}, {{t+|cdo|窓|tr=chŏng}}\n*: Hakka: {{t+|hak|窗仔|tr=chhûng-é}}, {{t+|hak|窗門|tr=chhûng-mùn}}\n*: Hokkien: {{t+|nan-hbl|窗仔門|tr=thang-á-mn̂g, thang-á-mûi}}, {{t+|nan-hbl|窗|tr=thang}}\n*: Jin: {{t+|cjy|窗戶|tr=cuon1 hu3}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|窗戶|tr=chuānghù}}, {{t+|cmn|窗口|tr=chuāngkǒu}}, {{t+|cmn|窗子|tr=chuāngzi}}, {{t+|cmn|牖|tr=yǒu}} {{qualifier|literary}}, {{t+|cmn|窗|tr=chuāng}} {{qualifier|literary}}, {{t+|cmn|軒|tr=xuān}} {{qualifier|literary}}, {{t+|cmn|櫳|tr=lóng}} {{qualifier|literary}}\n*: Wu: {{t+|wuu|窗頭}}, {{t+|wuu|窗門}}\n*: Xiang: {{t+|hsn|亮窗|tr=lian5 qyan1}}, {{t+|hsn|窗戶|tr=qyan1 fu}}\n* Chukchi: {{t+|ckt|ӄэргычьын|tr=qėrgyčʹyn}}\n* Chulym: {{t+|clw|täräčä}}\n* Chuvash: {{t+|cv|чӳрече}}\n* Circassian:\n*: East Circassian: {{t+|kbd|щхьэгъубжэ}}\n*: West Circassian: {{t+|ady|шъхьангъупчъэ}}\n* Coptic: {{t+|cop|ϣⲟⲩϣⲧ|m}}, {{t+|cop|ⲭⲁⲑⲏⲟⲩ|m}}\n* Cornish: {{t+|kw|fenester}}\n* Corsican: {{t+|co|finestra|f}}\n* Crimea